    "hard": [
      {
        "id": "r_hard_1",
        "category": "Craft and Structure",
        "skill": "Words in Context",
        "text": "The following text is from F. Scott Fitzgerald's 1925 novel The Great Gatsby.\n\n[Jay Gatsby] was balancing himself on the dashboard of his car with that resourcefulness of movement that is so peculiarly American\u2014that comes, I suppose, with the absence of lifting work in youth and, even more, with the formless grace of our nervous, sporadic games. This quality was continually breaking through his punctilious manner in the shape of restlessness.\n\nAs used in the text, what does the word \"quality\" most nearly mean?",
        "choices": [
          "Characteristic",
          "Standard",
          "Prestige",
          "Accomplishment"
        ],
        "correct": 0
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_2",
        "category": "Craft and Structure",
        "skill": "Text Structure and Purpose",
        "text": "Some studies have suggested that posture can influence cognition, but we should not overstate this phenomenon. A case in point: In a 2014 study, Megan O'Brien and Alaa Ahmed had subjects stand or sit while making risky simulated economic decisions. Standing is more physically unstable and cognitively demanding than sitting; accordingly, O'Brien and Ahmed hypothesized that standing subjects would display more risk aversion during the decision-making tasks than sitting subjects did, since they would want to avoid further feelings of discomfort and complicated risk evaluations. But O'Brien and Ahmed actually found no difference in the groups' performance.\n\nWhich choice best states the main purpose of the text?",
        "choices": [
          "It presents the study by O'Brien and Ahmed to critique the methods and results reported in previous studies of the effects of posture on cognition.",
          "It argues that research findings about the effects of posture on cognition are often misunderstood, as in the case of O'Brien and Ahmed's study.",
          "It explains a significant problem in the emerging understanding of posture's effects on cognition and how O'Brien and Ahmed tried to solve that problem.",
          "It discusses the study by O'Brien and Ahmed to illustrate why caution is needed when making claims about the effects of posture on cognition."
        ],
        "correct": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_3",
        "category": "Craft and Structure",
        "skill": "Text Structure and Purpose",
        "text": "The following text is from Herman Melville's 1854 short story \"The Lightning-Rod Man.\"\n\nThe stranger still stood in the exact middle of the cottage, where he had first planted himself. His singularity impelled a closer scrutiny. A lean, gloomy figure. Hair dark and lank, mattedly streaked over his brow. His sunken pitfalls of eyes were ringed by indigo halos, and played with an innocuous sort of lightning: the gleam without the bolt. The whole man was dripping. He stood in a puddle on the bare oak floor: his strange walking-stick vertically resting at his side.\n\nWhich choice best states the function of the underlined sentence (\"His singularity impelled a closer scrutiny.\") in the text as a whole?",
        "choices": [
          "It sets up the character description presented in the sentences that follow.",
          "It establishes a contrast with the description in the previous sentence.",
          "It elaborates on the previous sentence's description of the character.",
          "It introduces the setting that is described in the sentences that follow."
        ],
        "correct": 0
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_4",
        "category": "Craft and Structure",
        "skill": "Cross-Text Connections",
        "text": "Text 1: What factors influence the abundance of species in a given ecological community? Some theorists have argued that historical diversity is a major driver of how diverse an ecological community eventually becomes: differences in community diversity across otherwise similar habitats, in this view, are strongly affected by the number of species living in those habitats at earlier times.\n\nText 2: In 2010, a group of researchers including biologist Carla C\u00e1ceres created artificial pools in a New York forest. They stocked some pools with a diverse mix of zooplankton species and others with a single zooplankton species and allowed the pool communities to develop naturally thereafter. Over the course of four years, C\u00e1ceres and colleagues periodically measured the species diversity of the pools, finding\u2014contrary to their expectations\u2014that by the end of the study there was little to no difference in the pools' species diversity.\n\nBased on the texts, how would C\u00e1ceres and colleagues (Text 2) most likely describe the view of the theorists presented in Text 1?",
        "choices": [
          "It is largely correct, but it requires a minor refinement in light of the research team's results.",
          "It is not compelling as a theory regardless of any experimental data collected by the research team.",
          "It may seem plausible, but it is not supported by the research team's findings.",
          "It probably holds true only in conditions like those in the research team's study."
        ],
        "correct": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_5",
        "category": "Expression of Ideas",
        "skill": "Rhetorical Synthesis",
        "text": "While researching a topic, a student has taken the following notes:\n\n\u2022 Maika'i Tubbs is a Native Hawaiian sculptor and installation artist.\n\u2022 His work has been shown in the United States, Canada, Japan, and Germany, among other places.\n\u2022 Many of his sculptures feature discarded objects.\n\u2022 His work Erasure (2008) includes discarded audiocassette tapes and magnets.\n\u2022 His work Home Grown (2009) includes discarded pushpins, plastic plates and forks, and wood.\n\nThe student wants to emphasize a similarity between the two works. Which choice most effectively uses relevant information from the notes to accomplish this goal?",
        "choices": [
          "Erasure (2008) uses discarded objects such as audiocassette tapes and magnets; Home Grown (2009), however, includes pushpins, plastic plates and forks, and wood.",
          "Like many of Tubbs's sculptures, both Erasure and Home Grown include discarded objects: Erasure uses audiocassette tapes, and Home Grown uses plastic forks.",
          "Tubbs's work, which often features discarded objects, has been shown both within the United States and abroad.",
          "Tubbs completed Erasure in 2008 and Home Grown in 2009."
        ],
        "correct": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_6",
        "category": "Expression of Ideas",
        "skill": "Transitions",
        "text": "Iraqi artist Nazik Al-Malaika, celebrated as the first Arabic poet to write in free verse, didn't reject traditional forms entirely; her poem \"Elegy for a Woman of No Importance\" consists of two ten-line stanzas and a standard number of syllables. Even in this superficially traditional work, ______ Al-Malaika was breaking new ground by memorializing an anonymous woman rather than a famous man.\n\nWhich choice completes the text with the most logical transition?",
        "choices": [
          "in fact,",
          "though,",
          "therefore,",
          "moreover,"
        ],
        "correct": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_7",
        "category": "Standard English Conventions",
        "skill": "Form and Structure",
        "text": "Rabinal Ach\u00ed is a precolonial Maya dance drama performed annually in Rabinal, a town in the Guatemalan highlands. Based on events that occurred when Rabinal was a city-state ruled by a king, ______ had once been an ally of the king but was later captured while leading an invading force against him.\n\nWhich choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?",
        "choices": [
          "Rabinal Ach\u00ed tells the story of K'iche' Ach\u00ed, a military leader who",
          "K'iche' Ach\u00ed, the military leader in the story of Rabinal Ach\u00ed,",
          "there was a military leader, K'iche' Ach\u00ed, who in Rabinal Ach\u00ed",
          "the military leader whose story is told in Rabinal Ach\u00ed, K'iche' Ach\u00ed,"
        ],
        "correct": 0
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_8",
        "category": "Standard English Conventions",
        "skill": "Boundaries",
        "text": "According to Naomi Nakayama of the University of Edinburgh, the reason seeds from a dying dandelion appear to float in the air while ______ is that their porous plumes enhance drag, allowing the seeds to stay airborne long enough for the wind to disperse them throughout the surrounding area.\n\nWhich choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?",
        "choices": [
          "falling,",
          "falling:",
          "falling;",
          "falling"
        ],
        "correct": 3
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_9",
        "category": "Information and Ideas",
        "skill": "Command of Evidence (Quantitative)",
        "text": "Participants' Evaluation of the Likelihood That Robots Can Work Effectively in Different Occupations\n\nOccupation | Somewhat or very unlikely (%) | Neutral (%) | Somewhat or very likely (%)\ntelevision news anchor | 24 | 9 | 67\nteacher | 37 | 16 | 47\nfirefighter | 62 | 9 | 30\nsurgeon | 74 | 9 | 16\ntour guide | 10 | 8 | 82\n\nGeorgia Tech roboticists De'Aira Bryant and Ayanna Howard, along with ethicist Jason Borenstein, were interested in people's perceptions of robots' competence. They recruited participants and asked them how likely they think it is that a robot could do the work required in various occupations. Participants' evaluations varied widely depending on which occupation was being considered; for example, ______\n\nWhich choice most effectively uses data from the table to complete the example?",
        "choices": [
          "82% of participants believe that it is somewhat or very likely that a robot could work effectively as a tour guide, but only 16% believe that it is somewhat or very likely that a robot could work as a surgeon.",
          "47% of participants believe that it is somewhat or very likely that a robot could work effectively as a teacher, but 37% of respondents believe that it is somewhat or very unlikely that a robot could do so.",
          "9% of participants were neutral about whether a robot could work effectively as a television news anchor, which is the same percent of participants who were neutral when asked about a robot working as a surgeon.",
          "62% of participants believe that it is somewhat or very unlikely that a robot could work effectively as a firefighter."
        ],
        "correct": 0
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_10",
        "category": "Information and Ideas",
        "skill": "Inferences",
        "text": "Recent studies have shown that urban gardens provide multiple benefits beyond food production. They reduce local temperatures through shade and evapotranspiration, improve air quality by filtering pollutants, support biodiversity by creating habitat for insects and birds, and strengthen community bonds by providing shared spaces for residents to interact.\n\nBased on the text, which conclusion about urban gardens is most strongly supported?",
        "choices": [
          "Urban gardens are primarily valuable for food production.",
          "The temperature reduction effect is the most important benefit of urban gardens.",
          "Urban gardens provide environmental and social benefits simultaneously.",
          "Community interaction is impossible without urban gardens."
        ],
        "correct": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_11",
        "category": "Craft and Structure",
        "skill": "Cross-Text Connections",
        "text": "Text 1: Early theories of language acquisition proposed that children learn language primarily through imitation and reinforcement, gradually building vocabulary and grammar rules through repeated exposure and correction.\n\nText 2: Linguist Noam Chomsky challenged this view, arguing that the speed and consistency with which children acquire language across cultures suggests an innate biological capacity. Children, he noted, can generate sentences they've never heard before and understand complex grammatical structures with minimal explicit instruction.\n\nBased on the texts, how would Chomsky (Text 2) most likely respond to the theory presented in Text 1?",
        "choices": [
          "By arguing that imitation and reinforcement are the primary mechanisms of language learning",
          "By suggesting that innate biological factors play a more significant role than the theory acknowledges",
          "By agreeing that gradual exposure is the only way children learn language",
          "By dismissing the importance of vocabulary and grammar in language acquisition"
        ],
        "correct": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_12",
        "category": "Craft and Structure",
        "skill": "Words in Context",
        "text": "The scientist's research methodology was characterized by extraordinary rigor and precision. Every experiment was meticulously documented, variables were carefully controlled, and results were ______ analyzed before any conclusions were drawn.\n\nWhich choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?",
        "choices": [
          "hastily",
          "superficially",
          "exhaustively",
          "arbitrarily"
        ],
        "correct": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_13",
        "category": "Information and Ideas",
        "skill": "Command of Evidence",
        "text": "Historians have debated whether the Industrial Revolution improved or worsened living conditions for working-class families in 19th-century Britain.\n\nWhich quotation from a historical source would most effectively support the claim that living conditions worsened?",
        "choices": [
          "\"Factory owners invested heavily in new machinery and production techniques.\"",
          "\"Urban populations grew rapidly as workers migrated from rural areas seeking employment.\"",
          "\"Overcrowded tenements lacked adequate sanitation, and infectious diseases spread quickly among factory workers and their families.\"",
          "\"Some skilled workers formed unions to negotiate for better wages.\""
        ],
        "correct": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_14",
        "category": "Expression of Ideas",
        "skill": "Rhetorical Synthesis",
        "text": "A student researched the painter Frida Kahlo and took these notes:\n\n\u2022 Kahlo was a Mexican artist who lived from 1907 to 1954\n\u2022 She created 143 paintings, 55 of which were self-portraits\n\u2022 Her work often incorporated Mexican folk art traditions and indigenous symbolism\n\u2022 Kahlo's paintings explored themes of identity, postcolonialism, gender, and class\n\u2022 She had a complex relationship with fellow artist Diego Rivera\n\nThe student wants to emphasize Kahlo's focus on personal introspection in her art. Which choice most effectively accomplishes this goal?",
        "choices": [
          "Frida Kahlo, who lived from 1907 to 1954, created 143 paintings incorporating Mexican traditions.",
          "More than one-third of Frida Kahlo's 143 paintings were self-portraits, reflecting her intense focus on personal identity and self-examination.",
          "Kahlo's work explored themes of identity, postcolonialism, gender, and class in Mexican society.",
          "Mexican artist Frida Kahlo had a complex relationship with Diego Rivera and incorporated indigenous symbolism in her work."
        ],
        "correct": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_15",
        "category": "Standard English Conventions",
        "skill": "Form and Structure",
        "text": "The neuroscientist's findings, ______ challenged conventional understanding of memory formation, prompted a reevaluation of long-held theories in the field.\n\nWhich choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard English?",
        "choices": [
          "that",
          "which",
          "and they",
          "they"
        ],
        "correct": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_16",
        "category": "Information and Ideas",
        "skill": "Inferences",
        "text": "Archaeological evidence from ancient Mesopotamia shows that early urban centers developed sophisticated irrigation systems, centralized grain storage facilities, and specialized craftworkers. These findings suggest a level of social organization that required coordination, planning, and division of labor.\n\nWhich inference is most strongly supported by the text?",
        "choices": [
          "All ancient civilizations developed at the same rate and in the same manner.",
          "Early Mesopotamian cities had developed complex administrative structures to manage their resources.",
          "Irrigation was the only factor contributing to urban development in Mesopotamia.",
          "Specialized craftworkers worked independently without any coordination."
        ],
        "correct": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "r_hard_17",
        "category": "Craft and Structure",
        "skill": "Text Structure and Purpose",
        "text": "Marine biologists have long recognized that coral reefs serve as crucial habitats for countless species. However, recent research reveals an additional role: coral reefs act as natural breakwaters, reducing wave energy by up to 97% and protecting coastal communities from storm damage. This protective function has enormous economic value, preventing billions of dollars in coastal erosion and property damage annually.\n\nWhat is the primary purpose of this text?",
        "choices": [
          "To explain why coral reefs are difficult to study",
          "To present a newly recognized function of coral reefs beyond their known ecological role",
          "To argue that economic value is more important than ecological value",
          "To describe how waves damage coastal communities"
        ],
        "correct": 1
      }
    ]
