  "passages": [
    {
      "id": "passage_1",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "category": "Literature",
      "title": "Excerpt from 'The Awakening'",
      "source": "Kate Chopin, The Awakening (1899)",
      "text": "Mrs. Pontellier was not a woman given to confidences, a characteristic hitherto contrary to her nature. Even as a child she had lived her own small life all within herself. At a very early period she had apprehended instinctively the dual life\u2014that outward existence which conforms, the inward life which questions.\n\nThat summer at Grand Isle she began to loosen a little the mantle of reserve that had always enveloped her. It was not completely cast aside, but it was opened sufficiently to grant a glimpse of the warm, palpitating core beneath. Beneath the cool, composed surface, there lay passions and desires that even she herself had not fully comprehended.",
      "questions": [
        {
          "id": "passage_1_q1",
          "text": "Based on the passage, Mrs. Pontellier can best be described as:",
          "choices": [
            "Naturally outgoing and expressive",
            "Reserved but beginning to reveal her inner self",
            "Completely transformed from her former personality",
            "Indifferent to her own emotions and desires"
          ],
          "correct": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_1_q2",
          "text": "The phrase \"dual life\" most directly refers to:",
          "choices": [
            "Mrs. Pontellier's public behavior versus her private thoughts",
            "Her life before and after marriage",
            "Her childhood and adult personalities",
            "The contrast between summer and winter"
          ],
          "correct": 0
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_1_q3",
          "text": "Which choice provides the best evidence for the idea that Mrs. Pontellier was changing?",
          "choices": [
            "\"Mrs. Pontellier was not a woman given to confidences\"",
            "\"Even as a child she had lived her own small life all within herself\"",
            "\"That summer at Grand Isle she began to loosen a little the mantle of reserve\"",
            "\"Beneath the cool, composed surface, there lay passions and desires\""
          ],
          "correct": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "passage_2",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "category": "Science",
      "title": "CRISPR Gene Editing",
      "source": "Adapted from a scientific journal",
      "text": "CRISPR-Cas9, a revolutionary gene-editing technology, has transformed biological research and holds immense promise for treating genetic diseases. The system works by using a guide RNA to direct the Cas9 enzyme to a specific location in the genome, where it makes a precise cut in the DNA. This allows scientists to delete, replace, or insert genetic material with unprecedented accuracy.\n\nHowever, the technology is not without challenges. Off-target effects\u2014where the Cas9 enzyme cuts at unintended locations\u2014remain a concern. Researchers are working to improve the specificity of the system and reduce these unintended edits. Additionally, ethical questions arise regarding the use of CRISPR in human embryos, particularly concerning heritable genetic modifications.\n\nDespite these challenges, CRISPR has already demonstrated success in treating conditions such as sickle cell disease and certain forms of blindness. As the technology matures and regulatory frameworks develop, its applications in medicine are expected to expand significantly.",
      "questions": [
        {
          "id": "passage_2_q1",
          "text": "According to the passage, what is the primary function of the guide RNA in CRISPR-Cas9?",
          "choices": [
            "To cut the DNA at specific locations",
            "To direct the Cas9 enzyme to the correct genome location",
            "To replace defective genetic material",
            "To reduce off-target effects"
          ],
          "correct": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_2_q2",
          "text": "The passage suggests that a major concern with CRISPR technology is:",
          "choices": [
            "Its inability to treat genetic diseases",
            "The high cost of implementation",
            "Unintended cuts at wrong DNA locations",
            "Lack of research into its applications"
          ],
          "correct": 2
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_2_q3",
          "text": "Based on the passage, which statement about CRISPR's future is most accurate?",
          "choices": [
            "It will completely replace all other medical treatments",
            "Its medical applications are likely to grow as technology and regulations develop",
            "Ethical concerns will prevent any future use in humans",
            "It has already reached its maximum potential"
          ],
          "correct": 1
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "passage_3",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "category": "History",
      "title": "The Silk Road",
      "source": "Historical analysis",
      "text": "The Silk Road was not a single road, but rather a network of trade routes connecting the East and West for over 1,500 years. Beginning in the Han Dynasty of China (206 BCE \u2013 220 CE), these routes facilitated not just the exchange of silk, spices, and precious metals, but also the transmission of ideas, technologies, and cultural practices.\n\nThe impact of the Silk Road extended far beyond commerce. Buddhism spread from India to China along these routes, while Chinese innovations like papermaking and gunpowder eventually reached Europe. The exchange was reciprocal: Islamic scholars preserved and built upon Greek mathematical and philosophical texts, which later influenced the European Renaissance.\n\nHowever, the Silk Road also served as a conduit for the spread of diseases, including the bubonic plague. The same networks that connected civilizations and fostered cultural exchange also enabled pathogens to travel across continents, with devastating consequences.",
      "questions": [
        {
          "id": "passage_3_q1",
          "text": "The main purpose of this passage is to:",
          "choices": [
            "Describe the geographic route of the Silk Road",
            "Explain both positive and negative effects of the Silk Road",
            "Argue that the Silk Road was primarily about silk trade",
            "Focus exclusively on disease transmission"
          ],
          "correct": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_3_q2",
          "text": "According to the passage, which of the following traveled along the Silk Road?",
          "choices": [
            "Only physical goods like silk and spices",
            "Goods, ideas, technologies, and diseases",
            "Primarily religious texts and beliefs",
            "Mainly European innovations to Asia"
          ],
          "correct": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_3_q3",
          "text": "The passage suggests that the exchange along the Silk Road was:",
          "choices": [
            "One-directional from East to West",
            "Limited to the Han Dynasty period",
            "Reciprocal and multidirectional",
            "Focused only on commercial transactions"
          ],
          "correct": 2
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "passage_4",
      "difficulty": "easy",
      "category": "Social Science",
      "title": "Community Gardens",
      "source": "Urban planning study",
      "text": "Community gardens have become increasingly popular in urban areas over the past two decades. These shared spaces allow residents to grow their own fruits, vegetables, and flowers while fostering social connections with neighbors. Studies have shown that communities with active garden programs report higher levels of neighborhood satisfaction and social cohesion.\n\nThe benefits of community gardens extend beyond social connections. Participants often report increased physical activity, improved diet quality, and reduced grocery expenses. For children, community gardens provide hands-on learning experiences about nutrition, biology, and environmental stewardship.",
      "questions": [
        {
          "id": "passage_4_q1",
          "text": "According to the passage, community gardens provide:",
          "choices": [
            "Only opportunities to grow food",
            "Both social and individual benefits",
            "Expensive alternatives to grocery stores",
            "Limited educational value"
          ],
          "correct": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_4_q2",
          "text": "The passage suggests that community gardens are most valuable for:",
          "choices": [
            "Replacing traditional parks",
