          "text": "Based on the passage, children benefit from community gardens primarily through:",
          "choices": [
            "Reduced grocery costs for their families",
            "Hands-on learning about nutrition and nature",
            "Higher neighborhood satisfaction scores",
            "Increased property values"
          ],
          "correct": 1
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "passage_5",
      "difficulty": "hard",
      "category": "Science",
      "title": "Ocean Acidification",
      "source": "Environmental science research",
      "text": "The world's oceans are becoming more acidic at an unprecedented rate due to increased atmospheric carbon dioxide. When CO\u2082 dissolves in seawater, it forms carbonic acid, lowering the pH of ocean water. Since the Industrial Revolution, ocean pH has dropped by approximately 0.1 units\u2014representing a 30% increase in acidity.\n\nThis acidification poses serious threats to marine ecosystems, particularly organisms that build calcium carbonate shells or skeletons, such as corals, mollusks, and certain plankton species. As acidity increases, it becomes more difficult for these organisms to form and maintain their protective structures. Some species show impaired growth, reproduction, and survival in more acidic conditions.\n\nThe implications extend beyond individual species. Coral reefs, often called the rainforests of the sea, support approximately 25% of all marine life despite covering less than 1% of the ocean floor. Their degradation could trigger cascading effects throughout marine food webs. Additionally, certain plankton species that form the base of oceanic food chains are particularly vulnerable, potentially disrupting entire ecosystems and the human communities that depend on them for food and economic resources.",
      "questions": [
        {
          "id": "passage_5_q1",
          "text": "According to the passage, ocean acidification is primarily caused by:",
          "choices": [
            "Pollution from industrial waste",
            "Carbon dioxide dissolving in seawater",
            "Overfishing and habitat destruction",
            "Rising ocean temperatures"
          ],
          "correct": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_5_q2",
          "text": "The passage indicates that organisms most vulnerable to ocean acidification are those that:",
          "choices": [
            "Live in deep ocean environments",
            "Migrate long distances",
            "Build calcium carbonate structures",
            "Consume large amounts of plankton"
          ],
          "correct": 2
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_5_q3",
          "text": "The author mentions that coral reefs \"support approximately 25% of all marine life\" primarily to:",
          "choices": [
            "Explain why coral reefs are colorful",
            "Emphasize the potential widespread impact of reef degradation",
            "Argue that coral reefs should be protected from tourism",
            "Describe the physical structure of coral reefs"
          ],
          "correct": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "passage_5_q4",
          "text": "Which statement best describes the relationship between the second and third paragraphs?",
          "choices": [
            "The third paragraph refutes claims made in the second paragraph",
            "The third paragraph expands on the broader ecological implications introduced in the second paragraph",
