    {
      "id": "passage_6",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "category": "Science",
      "title": "Renewable Energy Storage",
      "source": "Technology research",
      "text": "One of the greatest challenges facing renewable energy adoption is not generation, but storage. Solar panels produce electricity only when the sun shines, and wind turbines generate power only when the wind blows. To make renewable energy reliable, we need effective ways to store excess energy generated during peak production times for use when production is low.\n\nBattery technology has advanced significantly in recent years, with lithium-ion batteries becoming more affordable and efficient. However, large-scale energy storage requires solutions beyond traditional batteries. Pumped hydroelectric storage, which uses excess electricity to pump water uphill and later releases it through turbines, currently provides about 95% of global energy storage capacity. Other promising technologies include compressed air energy storage, thermal storage using molten salts, and hydrogen fuel cells.\n\nThe development of efficient, cost-effective energy storage is crucial for the transition to renewable energy. As storage technology improves and becomes more economical, renewable energy sources will become increasingly competitive with fossil fuels, potentially accelerating the shift toward sustainable energy systems.",
      "questions": [
        {
          "id": "passage_6_q1",
          "text": "According to the passage, the main challenge with renewable energy is:",
          "choices": [
            "The cost of solar panels and wind turbines",
            "Storing energy for use when production is low",
